"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Langvalei I was born in 1125, in Great Bromley, Essex, England, his father, Hervey de Lanvallei, was 16 and his mother, Domina Matilda de Glanville, was 12. He married Gunnora St Clare about 1161, in Great Bromley, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1180, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1125–1180":"1125–1180","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1155–1205":"1155–1205","1110–1174":"1110–1174","1114–Female":"1114–Surnud","about 1161":"umbes 1161","1205":"1205","1125":"1125","1114":"1114","1155":"1155","1110":"1110","1174":"1174","1130":"1130","1180":"1180","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","Wakerley, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Wakerley, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1125–1180":"1125–1180","1130–Female":"1130–Kuo